Final-Project:PBS KIDS APP Data Analysis

Chen Chen

December, 2019

Data Introduction

The data is from Kaggle competition-2019 Data Science Bowl: Uncover the factors to help measure how young children learn. Here is the hyperlink for the competition:https://www.kaggle.com/c/data-science-bowl-2019/overview

The dataset contains data from the PBS app, in this app, children navigate a map and complete various levels, which may be activities, video clips, games, or assessments. Each assessment is designed to test a childs comprehension of a certain set of measurement-related skills. There are five assessments: Bird Measurer, Cart Balancer, Cauldron Filler, Chest Sorter, and Mushroom Sorter.

The intent of the competition is to use the gameplay data to forecast how many attempts a child will take to pass a given assessment (an incorrect answer is counted as an attempt).

Data wrangling

Credit to Eric, another player in the competition, he contributes his code and thanks to him, there is a initial cleaning version of data: https://www.kaggle.com/erikbruin/data-science-bowl-2019-eda-and-baseline

Data Explanation

variable X is an index used to connect dependent dataset x with independent y

columns Activity, Clip, Game, Assessment shows the number of those items before the selected assessment.

Session title has five variavles and they are the five assessments.

Those variables begins with X and followed a number means is an event type. E.g. event code 2000 always identifies the Start Game event for all games.

duration mean means the mean play time.

accumulated correct attempts means the number of correct attempts and uncorrect means uncorrect.

The X0-X3 means the accuracy-group, and it is also the definition of y.

3: the assessment was solved on the first attempt

2: the assessment was solved on the second attempt

1: the assessment was solved after 3 or more attempts

0: the assessment was never solved

Data Cleaning

choose meaningful and column that not all values equal to zero

x <- x[,1:102]
x <- x[c(-2,-7,-8,-12,-13,-14,-18,-19,-20,-21,-30,-31,-33,-34,-35,-36,-37,-39,-40,-43,-44,-45,-46,-47,-49)]
x <- x %>% 
  filter(duration_mean!=0)

Most of data is of right skewed distribution, so we use log transformation to change them into normal distribution

x[2:77] <- log(x[2:77]+1)

Then use Q3 + 1.5 * IQR to remove outliers

for (i in (2:77)){
    x <- x %>%
  filter(x[,i] <= quantile(x[,i], .75) + (1.5 * IQR(x[,i])))
  }

Merge x and y, then delete index

x <- merge(x,y,by.x="X",by.y="X0")
x <- x[,-1] 
x <- x %>% 
select(-X4230,-X4235,-X4080,-X4050)

Data Modeling

Data Partition: use stratified sampling

sample_set <- createDataPartition(x$accuracy_group, p = .8, list = FALSE)
x_train <- x[sample_set, ]
x_test <- x[-sample_set, ]

Logistic Regression

Because the dependent variable is a categorical variable, first we choose logistic regression model. We can see from that the variable session title. It is very reasonable as what type of assessment will largely decide the accuracy of the assessment. However, the residual deviance is not good as y is not much explained. The predicted accuracy is 0.6025017.

x_train0=x_train
x_test0=x_test
x_train0$accuracy_group=(x_train0$accuracy_group==0)
x_test0$accuracy_group=(x_test0$accuracy_group==0)
x_train1=x_train
x_test1=x_test
x_train1$accuracy_group=(x_train1$accuracy_group==1)
x_test1$accuracy_group=(x_test1$accuracy_group==1)
x_train2=x_train
x_test2=x_test
x_train2$accuracy_group=(x_train2$accuracy_group==2)
x_test2$accuracy_group=(x_test2$accuracy_group==2)
x_train3=x_train
x_test3=x_test
x_train3$accuracy_group=(x_train3$accuracy_group==3)
x_test3$accuracy_group=(x_test3$accuracy_group==3)

Decision Tree

Next, we try decision tree. The accuracy is 0.5858235

library(rpart)
tree_mod <-
  rpart(
    accuracy_group ~ .,
    method = "class",
    data = x_train,
    control = rpart.control(cp = 0.005) 
  )

tree_pred <- predict(tree_mod, x_test,  type = "class")

mean(x_test$accuracy_group==tree_pred)
## [1] 0.5837387

grid <- expand.grid(.mtry = c(3, 6, 9))

  trainControl(method = "cv",
               number = 3,
               selectionFunction = "best")
set.seed(1234)
rf.mod <-
  train(
    accuracy_group ~ .,
    data = x_train,
    method = "rf",
    metric = "Kappa",
    trControl = ctrl,
    tuneGrid = grid
  )

rf.pred <- predict(rf.mod, x_test, type = "raw")
